content: You generally prefer talking on the phone to texting.
You find adapting to new situations difficult.
If you were a professor, you would rather teach a course involving subjectivity and opinions (literature, philosophy, art), rather than something like math, science, engineering, or economics.
Seeing someone else cry can cause you to cry as well.
In your social circles, you tend to be a trendsetter.
You consider your imagination to be one of your biggest strengths.
You require alone time to recharge.
You value knowing and meeting a lot of people in the fields you're interested in.
You are comfortable with drawing a lot of attention to yourself if you are advocating for a cause you are passionate about.
You generally disagree with the status quo.
If you wanted to learn more about the climate movement, your go-to would be to attend a conference and meet some people.
When it comes to social issues, a startling fact or figure is more compelling to you than an individual's story.
A blank page excites you more than it intimidates you.
You gain a lot of satisfaction from completing tasks well.
The climate crisis is more of a people problem than a technological one.
Your ideal birthday party involves a few close friends or family members, as opposed to a large group of friends.
You would rather write a paper or article about the climate crisis than give a TED Talk about the climate crisis.
When faced with a challenge, you'd rather receive moral support over technical advice.
You often have the urge to create things.
You have a hard time letting things go.
In a classroom setting, you enjoy participating in discussions pertaining to topics you care about.
You value the truth above most things.
Given the choice, you’d rather write an essay than take a multiple choice test.
When cooking, you treat recipes more as inspiration than as instructions.
Your interest in the climate movement comes primarily from a place of empathy.
The idea of forging your own path within the climate movement is attractive.
A list of pros and cons can help you guide your decision-making, even when it goes against your gut feeling.
In your downtime, you feel the urge to socialize or spend time with friends.
You enjoy participating in friendly debates about complex issues.
Group activities interest you more than solo activities.
You believe that emotions often get in the way of sound decision-making.
You have been described as quiet, shy, or reserved.
When you buy something new, you tend to throw away the instructions and try to figure it out yourself.
You find yourself listening more than talking when you meet someone new.
The solution to the climate crisis already exists—we just need to start acting on it.
If money was of no concern, you would rather move into a beautifully furnished apartment instead of picking out the furniture for yourself.
The thought of meeting new people excites you more than it intimidates you.
You often act based on a “feeling,” even in situations where you can’t quite put it into words.
You find group discussions more draining than energizing.
You would rather carry out an established plan, as opposed to formulating the plan yourself.
People describe you as logical and pragmatic.
When you consume a piece of art (a movie, a painting, a song), you think about how you would have done it differently.
You adhere strictly to a set of rules that you've laid out for yourself.
You are prone to feeling overwhelmed in social situations.
You would find it much easier to get involved in the climate movement if someone gave you a specific need to fill.
